<h1>Privacy Policy — Actually</h1>
<p><em>Last updated: 29 June 2026</em></p>

<p>"Actually" ("the App", "we", "us") is a personal content-publishing tool used by its
owner to upload their own short videos to their own social-media accounts (such as TikTok
and YouTube). This policy explains what data the App handles.</p>

<h2>1. Who this applies to</h2>
<p>The App is operated by an individual creator for publishing their own content. It is not a
public consumer service and does not create accounts for, or collect data from, third-party
end users.</p>

<h2>2. What data we access</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>TikTok account information</strong> — when you authorize the App, TikTok provides a
  user identifier (open ID), basic profile information, and an access token. These are used only
  to upload videos to your own authorized account.</li>
  <li><strong>Video files</strong> — the video files you choose are uploaded to TikTok on your behalf.</li>
</ul>

<h2>3. How we use it</h2>
<p>Data is used solely to authenticate with TikTok and to upload your videos to your own account.
We do not use it for advertising, profiling, or any unrelated purpose.</p>

<h2>4. Storage</h2>
<p>Access tokens are stored locally on the operator's own computer (in a file named
<code>tiktok_token.json</code>) only to avoid logging in repeatedly. Nothing is uploaded to any
third-party server other than TikTok's own official API endpoints.</p>

<h2>5. Sharing</h2>
<p>We do not sell, rent, or share any data with third parties. Data is exchanged only with TikTok's
official API to perform the uploads you request.</p>

<h2>6. Data retention &amp; deletion</h2>
<p>Locally stored tokens can be deleted at any time by removing the token file. You may also revoke
the App's access from your TikTok account settings at any time.</p>

<h2>7. Contact</h2>
<p>For any questions about this policy, contact: <a href="mailto:marcturkesteen@gmail.com">marcturkesteen@gmail.com</a>.</p>

